  "prompt_text": "A company's revenue grew 20% per year for 5 years. If initial revenue was $1M, what is the final revenue and total revenue over the period?",
  "response_text": "To calculate the final revenue after a 20% annual growth rate for 5 years, we will use the formula for compound annual growth rate (CAGR):\n\nFinal Revenue = Initial Revenue * (1 + Growth Rate)^Number of Years\nFinal Revenue = $1,000,000 * (1 + 0.20)^5\nFinal Revenue = $1,000,000 * (1.20)^5\nFinal Revenue = $1,000,000 * 2.48832\nFinal Revenue ≈ $2,488,320\n\nTo calculate the total revenue over the period, we can use the formula for the sum of a geometric series:\n\nTotal Revenue = Initial Revenue * ((1 + Growth Rate)^Number of Years - 1) / Growth Rate\nTotal Revenue = $1,000,000 * ((1.20^5 - 1) / 0.20)\nTotal Revenue = $1,000,000 * ((2.48832 - 1) / 0.20)\nTotal Revenue = $1,000,000 * (1.48832 / 0.20)\nTotal Revenue = $1,000,000 * 7.4416\nTotal Revenue ≈ $7,441,600\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
